1. try
....................................
The try block contains code that may throw an exception.

Banking Example
public class Bank {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int balance = 5000;
        int withdrawAmount = 1000;

        try {

            int remainingBalance = balance - withdrawAmount;

            System.out.println("Remaining Balance: " + remainingBalance);

        } catch (Exception e) {

            System.out.println("Transaction Failed");
        }
    }
}

Output
....................................
Remaining Balance: 4000

Use Case: Withdrawal, fund transfer, payment processing.

2. catch
....................................
The catch block handles exceptions thrown inside the try block.

Banking Example
public class Bank {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        try {

            int amount = 1000 / 0;

        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {

            System.out.println("Invalid Transaction");
        }
    }
}

Output
....................................
Invalid Transaction

Use Case: Invalid calculations, payment failures, database exceptions.

3. finally
....................................
The finally block always executes whether an exception occurs or not.

Banking Example
public class Bank {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        try {

            System.out.println("Transaction Started");

        } finally {

            System.out.println("Closing Database Connection");
        }
    }
}

Output

Transaction Started
Closing Database Connection

Use Case:

Close database connection
Close file
Release resources
Close network connection


4. throw
....................................

The throw keyword is used to manually throw an exception.

Banking Example
public class Bank {

    public static void withdraw(double balance, double amount) {

        if (amount > balance) {

            throw new RuntimeException("Insufficient Balance");
        }

        System.out.println("Withdrawal Successful");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        withdraw(5000, 7000);
    }
}

Output
....................................
Exception in thread "main"
java.lang.RuntimeException:
Insufficient Balance

Use Case:

Insufficient balance
Invalid account number
Invalid PIN
5. throws
....................................
The throws keyword declares that a method may throw an exception, leaving handling to the caller.

Banking Example
import java.io.IOException;

class BankStatement {

    public void downloadStatement() throws IOException {

        throw new IOException("Unable to Download Statement");
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        BankStatement statement = new BankStatement();

        try {

            statement.downloadStatement();

        } catch (IOException e) {

            System.out.println(e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

Output
....................................
Unable to Download Statement

Use Case:

File handling
Database operations
Network communication


6. assert
....................................

assert is used during development to verify assumptions. If the condition is false and assertions are enabled (-ea), an AssertionError is thrown.

Banking Example
public class Bank {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        double balance = 5000;

        assert balance >= 0 : "Balance cannot be negative";

        System.out.println("Account is Valid");
    }
}

Output (Assertions Enabled)
....................................
Account is Valid

If:

double balance = -500;

Output:

java.lang.AssertionError:
Balance cannot be negative

Use Case:

Validate internal business rules
Check developer assumptions
Debugging and testing

Note: Assertions are disabled by default. Run the JVM with -ea (Enable Assertions) to activate them.
....................................
throw vs throws
throw	throws
Used to explicitly throw an exception	Declares that a method may throw an exception
Used inside a method	Used in the method signature
Throws one exception object at a time	Can declare multiple exception types

Example: throw new RuntimeException();	Example: void read() throws IOException

Interview Summary
Keyword	Banking Example

try	  Fund transfer, withdrawal
catch	Handle transaction failure
finally	Close database connection
throw	Throw "Insufficient Balance" exception
throws	Declare file/database exceptions
assert	Verify account balance or business rules during development